   210	ephemeris-refresh cadence supports the chosen age.
   211	
   212	---
   213	
   214	## 3. Caution band, revoke backstop, dwells, and ACK timeout
   215	
   216	The metric for the caution/revoke scalars is the horizontal-accuracy metre value (§0.1);
   217	`dwell_clear`, `dwell_rearm`, `T_ack` are seconds. Ordering constraint (`SAFETY_CASE.md`
   218	§3.2): `caution_clear (60) < caution_enter (75) < revoke_threshold (100)`.
   219	
   220	### 3.1 `revoke_threshold` — `100 m`
   221	
   222	**Derivation.** A single, profile-independent hard horizontal-accuracy ceiling at which the
   223	metric forces WARNING (`metric < revoke_threshold` is a G2 conjunct in `lib.rs`). Set equal to
   224	the **denied** horizontal PL (§1.1) so that in denied operation the scalar backstop and the
   225	profile PL revoke together, and in aided operation the tighter 12 m profile PL trips first. It
   226	is a backstop against a mis-set or absent profile limit, not the primary bound.
   227	
   228	**Sensitivity.** 2× loose (200 m): coincides with the raw denied *acceptance* error number —
   229	no per-epoch margin. 2× tight (50 m): would override the denied profile PL and revoke denied
   230	operation at half its intended envelope.
   231	
   232	**Validation plan.** Same withheld-replay coverage study as §1.1; confirm the scalar backstop
   233	never binds tighter than the intended active profile.
   234	
   235	### 3.2 `caution_enter` — `75 m` · `caution_clear` — `60 m`
   236	
   237	**Derivation.** The caution band summons the helm *before* revocation. Referenced to the
   238	**denied** envelope (where the ladder is most safety-relevant — the all-LEO-loss DR growth
   239	toward 100 m): pre-alert on ≥ 75 m (75 % of the 100 m revoke), clear on ≤ 60 m sustained for
   240	`dwell_clear`. The 15 m entry/clear separation is real hysteresis against metric noise near the
   241	threshold (H3). **Consequence of single-scalar thresholds:** in *aided* operation the metric
   242	sits far inside 12 m, so this band never fires — aided mode has no caution pre-alert. This is
   243	the profile-independence limitation registered in §5.1; the values are chosen to make the
   244	ladder meaningful in the mode where it matters most.
   245	
   246	**Sensitivity.** Entry 2× (150 m): above the 100 m revoke — CAUTION could never precede
   247	WARNING, defeating the pre-alert. Entry too near clear (narrow band): alarm chatter. Clear too
   248	low: caution annunciation lingers after genuine recovery.
   249	
   250	**Validation plan.** Replay the degrading-geometry / LEO-loss trajectory and tune the band so
   251	the helm gets a stable, useful lead time before revoke without chatter; **strongly recommend
   252	adopting the §5.1 per-profile caution band** so aided mode regains a pre-alert.
   253	
   254	### 3.3 `dwell_clear` — `5 s`
   255	
   256	**Derivation.** Sustained-recovery dwell before CAUTION→NOMINAL clears (on top of the 60/75 m
   257	hysteresis). ~5 s ≈ 25 solution frames at 5 Hz — enough to confirm the metric has genuinely
   258	settled below `caution_clear`, short enough not to strand a stale soft-alert. Human-factors /
   259	anti-flap reasoning; no trial evidence yet.
   260	
   261	**Sensitivity.** 2× tight (2.5 s): metric noise can re-trip caution → soft-alert flapping. 2×
   262	loose (10 s): recovered solution still annunciates caution, eroding helm trust in the alert.
   263	
   264	**Validation plan.** Replay metric-noise near the clear threshold; sea-trial helm feedback on
   265	alert stability.
   266	
   267	### 3.4 `dwell_rearm` — `10 s`
   268	
   269	**Derivation.** Minimum dwell after a latched revocation (state L) before a helm re-arm can
   270	re-grant (L→N guard, `SAFETY_CASE.md` §2.2). Longer than `dwell_clear` because re-granting
   271	authority is higher-stakes than clearing a soft alert: it forces the fault condition to have
   272	genuinely cleared and a deliberate, considered helm re-arm, preventing arm/fault/arm cycling
   273	(H3). Proposed **10 s**.
   274	
   275	**Sensitivity.** 2× tight (5 s): rapid re-arm after a transient fault risks authority cycling.
   276	2× loose (20 s): operationally frustrating recovery after a genuinely transient condition,
   277	tempting the helm to steer manually / distrust the system.
   278	
   279	**Validation plan.** Fault-injection replay of transient-then-recover sequences; sea-trial helm
   280	workflow feedback. (Note the open `latched_since_ns`-keying test item from `DECISIONS.md` D33
   281	interacts with this dwell — fresh-from-DISARMED arms.)
   282	
   283	### 3.5 `T_ack` — `10 s`
   284	
   285	**Derivation.** Time in WARNING with no helm ACK before escalation to ESCALATED/max alarm
   286	(`SAFETY_CASE.md` §2.2/§3.2). Because the terminal state is **non-kinetic** (software never
   287	manoeuvres), `T_ack` sizes *attention-summoning*, not collision avoidance: a helm should
   288	acknowledge a loud alarm within a few seconds; ~10 s escalates promptly without escalating on a
   289	helm who is mid-action. It is nonetheless bounded by the vessel manoeuvre/collision time budget
   290	(displacement-hull assumption); a planing/fast boat shrinks it (`SAFETY_CASE.md` vessel-speed
   291	caveat).
   292	
   293	**Sensitivity.** 2× tight (5 s): premature escalation → alarm fatigue / desensitisation. 2×
   294	loose (20 s): slow escalation eats into the manoeuvre budget on a fast boat.
   295	
   296	**Validation plan.** Human-factors alarm-response measurement in the trial environment; re-derive
   297	against the actual hull's manoeuvre/collision time budget before trials.
   298	
   299	---
   300	
   301	## 4. Tracker detection-threshold false-alarm analysis (U-T1 finding F9)
   302	
   303	Finding F9 (`DECISIONS.md` D36) routes the `pnt-tracker` default detection threshold of **32**
   304	(15.1 dB) here for a probability-of-false-alarm (PFA) analysis. The tracker's per-block quality
   305	statistic is `Q = peak_delay_bin_power / mean_of_the_other_delay_bins_power`, maximised over
   306	the frequency-hypothesis grid (`crates/pnt-tracker/src/lib.rs`). The fixture geometry is
   307	**256 delay bins × 256 frequency bins** (Fs = 8192, N = 256, 32 Hz coarse grid). Measured
   308	noise-only quality statistics over 4000 pure-noise blocks: **median 11.5, p99 15.7, max 20.0**;
   309	threshold 32.
   310	
   311	### 4.1 Analytic model
   312	
   313	**Statistic → Fisher's g.** Within one frequency hypothesis, the N_d = 256 circular-correlation
   314	delay-bin powers are (under the assumptions below) i.i.d. exponential (complex-Gaussian
   315	magnitude-squared). Let `S` be their sum and `P_max` the peak. The code's floor is the mean of
   316	the **other** N_d−1 bins, so
   317	
   318	```
   319	Q = P_max / [ (S − P_max) / (N_d − 1) ] = (N_d − 1) · g / (1 − g),   where g = P_max / S.
   320	```
   321	
   322	`g` is exactly **Fisher's g-statistic** (largest ordinate / sum) for the max of N_d i.i.d.
   323	exponentials, whose exact exceedance is
   324	
   325	```
   326	P(g > x) = Σ_{j=1}^{⌊1/x⌋} (−1)^{j−1} · C(N_d, j) · (1 − j·x)^{N_d − 1}.
   327	```
   328	
   329	Inverting the map, threshold `Q` corresponds to `g_thr = Q / (Q + N_d − 1)`. For the reported
   330	quality the tracker also **maximises over the N_f = 256 frequency rows**, so the per-block PFA
   331	is bounded by a union over rows:
   332	
   333	```
   334	P_block(Q) ≤ N_f · P(g > g_thr) ≈ N_f · N_d · (1 − g_thr)^{N_d − 1}
   335	           = N_cells · (1 − g_thr)^{N_d − 1},   N_cells = 65536.
   336	```
   337	
   338	(The leading Fisher term dominates by >10 orders of magnitude at these thresholds; higher-order
   339	terms are negligible.)
   340	
   341	### 4.2 Model validation against the measured noise statistics
   342	
   343	Inverting `P_block` for the quantile thresholds and comparing to the empirical 4000-block
   344	statistics (independent-cell prediction vs observed):
   345	
   346	| Quantile | P_block | Q predicted (i.i.d. cells) | Q observed |
   347	|---|---:|---:|---:|
   348	| median | 0.5 | 12.06 | **11.5** |
   349	| p99 | 0.01 | 16.19 | **15.7** |
   350	| max (≈1/4000) | 2.5e-4 | 20.14 | **20.0** |
   351	
   352	The model reproduces all three empirical quantiles to within ~0.5 in Q. The observed values sit
   353	**slightly below** the independent-cell prediction, and the gap narrows toward the tail —
   354	exactly the signature of **mild positive inter-cell correlation** reducing the effective number
   355	of independent cells. This self-consistency is strong evidence the model is appropriate for the
   356	fixture, and it makes the independent-cell PFA a **slightly optimistic** (i.e. conservative to
   357	inflate) estimate.
   358	
   359	### 4.3 PFA at threshold 32, and the false-alarm rate
   360	
   361	At Q = 32: `g_thr = 32/287 = 0.1115`, giving
   362	
   363	```
   364	P_block(32) ≈ 65536 · (0.8885)^255 ≈ 5.3e-9   (independent-cell estimate).
   365	```
   366	
   367	Threshold 32 sits ~12 above the observed noise-only max of 20.0 — a very safe false-alarm
   368	operating point. As a rate: the fixture block is 256/8192 = 31.25 ms (~32 blocks/s per tracked
   369	signal), so per-tracker FA rate ≈ 32 × 5.3e-9 ≈ 1.7e-7 s⁻¹ → **mean time between false alarms
   370	≈ 68 days per tracker** (~7 days across ~10 simultaneous trackers). For a conservative bracket
   371	covering cell-correlation and non-ideal-reference tail fattening (below), treat the true PFA as
   372	**order 1e-8** rather than 5e-9.
   373	
   374	### 4.4 Assumptions and caveats (including cell correlation)
   375	
   376	- **A1 — i.i.d. exponential delay bins.** Exact only for white input noise and an ideal
   377	  delta-autocorrelation reference. **Real Starlink PSS/SSS, Iridium, Orbcomm sequences have
   378	  non-zero autocorrelation sidelobes** → off-peak bins are correlated and not identically
   379	  distributed → the effective independent-cell count is **below** N_d and the tail is **heavier**
   380	  than exponential. This is the dominant reason the synthetic-fixture PFA cannot be trusted as
   381	  the production PFA. (No real sequences are shipped — U-T1 `[UNVERIFIED]`.)
   382	- **A2 — row union bound.** The N_f frequency rows are **positively correlated** (same IQ block;
   383	  the 32 Hz grid equals the FFT bin spacing Fs/N, so a row shift is a circular re-index), so the
   384	  union bound over-counts and `P_block` is an **upper** bound. The empirical quantiles sitting
   385	  below the independent-cell prediction confirm the direction.
   386	- **A3 — stationary white Gaussian noise.** Real captures carry coloured noise, narrowband
   387	  interference lines, ADC quantization, dropouts and sea-surface multipath. The per-row CFAR
   388	  normalisation self-adapts to broadband level changes but **not** to a narrowband interferer
   389	  that mimics a correlation peak → real tails fatten.
   390	- **A4 — fixture geometry ≠ production.** Fs = 8192, N = 256, 32 Hz grid, 256×256 cells are the
   391	  **test fixture**. Production is 2.5–5 MHz bandwidth with real-length sequences; both N_cells and
   392	  the block duration change, so **both the PFA and the block rate must be recomputed for
   393	  production geometry**. Threshold 32 is validated *for the fixture*, not frozen for production.
   394	
   395	### 4.5 Proposed threshold policy
   396	
   397	1. **Keep the peak-to-mean-of-others ratio (CFAR) statistic.** Its scale-invariance to input
   398	   noise power is a genuine robustness property for a maritime RF environment with a changing
   399	   noise floor — prefer it over any absolute-power threshold.
   400	2. **Set the threshold from a target per-block PFA via the Fisher-g model scaled to the actual
   401	   production search volume**, not a magic constant: solve `N_cells^prod · (1 − g)^{N_d^prod − 1}
   402	   = PFA_target` with `g = Q/(Q + N_d^prod − 1)`. This makes the threshold grow ~logarithmically
   403	   with search volume (Bonferroni/CFAR-consistent) as N and the Doppler span change.
   404	3. **Choose `PFA_target` from a false-observation budget, not from minimising PFA.** The tracker
   405	   is the **first** gate; a spurious detection still faces the EKF per-component 1-DOF chi-square
   406	   NIS gate, the 5° elevation mask, the ephemeris-age gate, the pass-nuisance state and cross-
   407	   sensor residuals. A per-block PFA of ~1e-7 to ~1e-8 in production geometry (≈ <1 false
   408	   detection per hours-to-days per tracker) is a reasonable starting budget, leaving the EKF gate
   409	   as the second line. (At the fixture, ~1e-7 corresponds to Q ≈ 29; 32 gives ~5e-9.)
   410	4. **The missed-detection cost sets the *upper* bound on the threshold.** Too high → fewer
   411	   accepted Doppler observations → weaker geometry → larger protection limits → authority harder
   412	   to sustain and convergence slower. The threshold is a **detection/false-alarm trade-off to be
   413	   set jointly with the per-constellation link budget** (C/N₀), which is currently `[UNVERIFIED]`
   414	   (no per-constellation C/N₀ measurements). Do **not** maximise for low PFA in isolation.
   415	5. **Validate on real noise-only and weak-signal captures**, using this Fisher-g model only as
   416	   the analytic scaffold. Deploy a threshold set from measured real-capture noise statistics with
   417	   explicit margin above the measured noise-only max (the fixture shows 32 ≈ 12 above max 20).
   418	
   419	**Fixture recommendation:** retain the explicit default **32** (PFA ~5e-9, ~12 above observed
   420	noise max) as a conservative provisional. **Production threshold: `[UNVERIFIED]`**, to be
   421	re-derived per §4.5(2)–(5) once real sequences, production geometry and per-constellation link
   422	budgets exist. The tracker threshold is **not** an `AuthorityParams` field and is not in the
   423	appendix; it is nonetheless a steering-relevant `[UNVERIFIED]` value with its own freeze path.
   424	
   425	---
   426	
   427	## 5. Open design issues registered by this proposal
   428	
   429	### 5.1 Single-scalar caution/revoke thresholds vs per-profile protection limits
   430	
   431	`AuthorityParams` carries `ProtectionLimits` **per profile** (aided/denied, 8× apart on
   432	position) but `caution_enter`/`caution_clear`/`revoke_threshold` are **single scalars** compared
   433	against the same metre metric. With the aided PL at 12 m and the caution band referenced to the
   434	100 m denied envelope, **aided mode has no caution pre-alert** — the profile PL revokes before
   435	the caution metric is ever reached. This proposal makes the band meaningful in the mode where it
   436	matters most (denied/degrading) and accepts the aided-mode gap. **Recommended contracts change:
   437	make the caution band (and revoke backstop) per-profile**, matching `ProtectionLimits`. Routed
   438	to the contracts owner as a proposed v6 refinement; not assumed here.
   439	
   440	### 5.2 Coverage-factor / acceptance-percentile coupling
   441	
   442	The `k = 2` position factor and the velocity/heading mappings all stand in for the baseline's
   443	**unfrozen acceptance-percentile/confidence definition**. When that definition is frozen (baseline
   444	obligation), every §1 limit must be re-derived consistently. The two are a single coupled freeze,
   445	not independent.
   446	
   447	### 5.3 Values with the weakest evidentiary support
   448	
   449	`t_dr` (no LEO-gap replay statistics), the aided velocity PL 0.014 m/s (achievability unproven;
   450	4 Hz tracker scale is fixture-only), and the human-factors dwells/`T_ack` (no trial evidence)
   451	are the least-anchored proposals. See the summary paragraph.
   452	
