   127	## v3 (2026-07-22)
   128	
   129	v3 retains v1 and v2 and resolves D10, D13, and review findings F3/F4.
   130	
   131	### Estimator state and epoch uncertainty
   132	
   133	`FilterState` carries ECEF position and velocity, heading, primary receiver-clock bias and
   134	drift, and the estimator's complete row-major covariance together with its dimension. The
   135	nine core slots are ordered position ECEF (0--2), velocity ECEF (3--5), heading (6), clock
   136	bias metres (7), and clock drift metres/second (8). Dynamically registered states follow.
   137	`SolutionEpoch` exposes horizontal-position, horizontal-speed, and vertical one-sigma
   138	accuracies in SI units, derived from that epoch's covariance. For source compatibility with
   139	the v2 executive these are accessors rather than additional stored fields; U-I2 shall move
   140	epoch creation to a constructor before any wire schema represents them as stored fields.
   141	Position covariance is rotated from ECEF into ENU at the epoch position. Horizontal
   142	accuracy is 2-D DRMS, `sqrt(P_ENU[E,E] + P_ENU[N,N])`; because the complete rotation is
   143	applied, ECEF cross-covariances contribute. Vertical accuracy is the ENU up-axis one-sigma,
   144	`sqrt(P_ENU[U,U])`. Speed accuracy applies the same 2-D DRMS convention to the ECEF
   145	velocity covariance. `horizontal_velocity_ned_mps` is the north/east projection of ECEF
   146	velocity at the epoch position, and the speed-through-water model is its horizontal norm.
   147	
   148	The primary clock-bias state is retained for future pseudorange/STL observability and to
   149	preserve the baseline's required state surface. Doppler currently observes drift, not bias,
   150	so propagation applies the standard two-state integrated drift-noise covariance and caps
   151	clock-bias variance at `1e8 m^2` for the primary and registered receiver clocks. That cap and
   152	the process-noise coefficient are engineering bounds pending replay tuning `[UNVERIFIED]`.
   153	
   154	GNSS aiding uses six sequential scalar, one-degree-of-freedom updates (three ECEF position,
   155	then three ECEF velocity). A supplied chi-square threshold is therefore a per-component
   240	
   241	## v5 (2026-07-23)
   242	
   243	v5 retains v1--v4.1 and replaces the fail-open integrity placeholder with the authority
   244	supervisor contract from `SAFETY_CASE.md` §1--§3.
   245	
   246	`AuthorityParams` carries separate aided and denied `ProtectionLimits` for horizontal
   247	position (m), horizontal velocity (m/s), and heading (rad), plus `Option<f64>` fields for
   248	`t_lease`, `t_dr`, `t_eph`, `dwell_clear`, `dwell_rearm`, `caution_enter`,
   249	`caution_clear`, `revoke_threshold`, and `T_ack` (seconds for all time values). Every
   250	numeric must be present, finite, and non-negative. If any field is `None` or invalid, the
   251	supervisor can never grant steering authority. This is the literal D17 fail-closed gate;
   252	there are no numeric defaults.
   253	
   254	The supervisor consumes clock-service monotonic nanoseconds only, `ArmCommand`, solution
   255	sequence and covariance-derived horizontal-position/horizontal-velocity/heading accuracies,
   256	active profile, last-absolute-observation time, ephemeris age/integrity, and calibration ID.
   257	Calibration identity is checked by an injected validator; absence is always rejection and
   258	the default validator accepts any present, non-empty ID. **Amended by v5.1; see below.** A renewing frame is exactly
   259	`sequence advanced && G2 && G3`, independent of current lease state. Deadline equality is
   260	expiry. Arm defaults false, disarm withdraws G1, and every fault revocation clears the arm
   261	latch so a fresh arm command is required.
   262	
   263	Outputs are `AuthorityOutput { steering_authorised, state, alarm, transition }`. `transition`
   264	identifies only supervisor state transitions. The output type deliberately has no vehicle
   265	mode, manoeuvre, RTL, Loiter, or disarm command. The six states, eleven events, guarded arm
   266	cells, destination-state authority/annunciation, simultaneous priority, dwells, ACK timeout,
   267	and latched recovery are exactly the total matrix in `SAFETY_CASE.md` §2.2.
   268	
   269	The executive routes `ArmCommand` only to integrity and supplies every emitted solution to
   270	the supervisor before deriving `SolutionEpoch.steering_authorised`. Its production-default
   271	skeleton constructor installs the real supervisor with an incomplete parameter register and
   272	is therefore fail-closed. `test_stub` remains explicitly stub-backed for focused legacy
   273	executive tests.
   274	
   275	## v5.1 (2026-07-23)
   276	
   277	v5.1 amends, but does not replace, v5. `AckCommand` is the helm acknowledgement sibling of
   278	`ArmCommand` on the measurement bus. It carries clock-service-stamped
   279	`host_monotonic_ns: u64` and `source_id: SourceId`, is journalled, and is routed by the
   280	executive only to `IntegrityAuthorityGate::acknowledge`; it never enters the estimator.
   281	Acknowledgement changes annunciation/latch state only as specified by the §2.2 matrix and
   282	does not itself restore steering authority.
    80	| Dual magnetometers to fusion executive | 10 Hz each nominal (**estimate**). |
    81	| Speed log to fusion executive | 5 Hz nominal (**estimate**). |
    82	| LEO Doppler observations | Event-driven at each valid correlation solution; target 1 Hz per tracked signal (**estimate**). No synthetic observation is emitted to satisfy a rate. |
    83	| GNSS measurement/truth input | Native receiver rate, at least 1 Hz (**estimate**); routing is determined before fusion by `gnss_authority`. |
    84	| Navigation/integrity solution | 5 Hz nominal (**estimate**), using propagated dead-reckoned fill between absolute observations. |
    85	| MAVLink `GPS_INPUT` output | 5 Hz nominal (handoff requirement: approximately 5 Hz), continuously while the process is healthy, subject to steering-authority gating. |
    86	| Journal writes | Every input, decision and output event, preserving native rate; batched disk flush is allowed only if crash-loss bounds are explicitly configured (**estimate**). |
    87	
    88	The four-second `GPS_TIMEOUT_MS` motivates continuous output but does not define estimator
    89	validity. Any dead-reckoning timeout shall govern **steering authority only**. It shall never
    90	stop propagation, observation processing, journalling, or the 10--20 minute position
    91	convergence process.
    92	
   148	## Acceptance profiles
   149	
   150	These are system-level trial limits, evaluated against an independent truth journal over
   151	declared test segments. They do not replace per-epoch integrity and authority checks.
   152	Velocity means horizontal per-axis error; position means horizontal error. Exact percentile,
   153	window and confidence definitions remain `[UNVERIFIED]` and must be frozen before trials.
   154	
   155	| Criterion | Aided (`production`) | Denied (`recorded_only` or `off`) |
   156	|---|---:|---:|
   157	| Horizontal position error | <= 25 m (**estimate**, operational-grade target inferred from the handoff's example of a correct operational limit) | <= 200 m after an uninterrupted 20-minute constant-heading convergence leg (**estimate**, conservative edge of the stated approximately 100--200 m expectation) |
   158	| Horizontal velocity error, each axis | <= 0.02 m/s (**estimate**, operational target within the handoff's 0.007--0.04 m/s expectation) | <= 0.04 m/s (**estimate**, upper edge of the stated 0.7--4 cm/s expectation) |
   159	| Heading error | <= 2 degrees (**estimate**) | <= 5 degrees (**estimate**) |
   160	| Horizontal current-vector error | Recorded and scored, but no pass/fail threshold until local truth instrumentation and current variability are characterised (`[UNVERIFIED]`) | Same; omission of a threshold does not make publication optional |
   161	| Output continuity | Valid `GPS_INPUT` at nominal 5 Hz while healthy; no gap >= 4 s (**estimate** derived from the stated timeout) | Same; dead-reckoned fill is explicitly permitted, with reported uncertainty and authority enforced upstream |
   162	| GNSS isolation | GNSS fusion is allowed and auditable | Zero GNSS measurements delivered to fusion; `recorded_only` may write truth only |
   163	| Replay determinism | Same raw log, config, software and deterministic execution settings produces bit-exact journal outputs; explicitly non-deterministic backends require a frozen numeric tolerance `[UNVERIFIED]` | Same, including a paired GNSS-withheld replay used for headline results |
   164	
   165	The aided numbers are engineering estimates, not literature-derived guarantees. Here,
   166	“operational-grade” means satisfying the estimated 25 m position, 0.02 m/s per-axis
   167	velocity, and 2 degree heading trial targets while integrity permits steering. It does not
   168	mean certified safety performance. The denied limit intentionally does not inherit the
   169	aided 25 m position target, which would make the research result fail by construction.
   170	The 2/5 degree heading gates are provisional engineering targets chosen to bound transverse
   171	velocity error from heading-rotated speed-log measurements while allowing degraded magnetic
   172	operation; the handoff supplies no validated heading limit, so both require trial validation
   173	and are `[UNVERIFIED]`.
   174	
   175	The real horizontal and speed uncertainty monitor and every steering gate shall live in
   176	the companion process upstream of MAVLink, because the handoff states that ArduPilot
   177	internally clamps reported horizontal accuracy at 100 m. Report `horiz_accuracy` and
   178	`speed_accuracy` independently in `GPS_INPUT`. Publish fused heading through the
   179	`GPS_INPUT.yaw` field with its validity governed by the companion integrity gate. `ODOMETRY`
   180	shall not be used for this navigation injection because its ArduPilot path cannot transport
   181	the required per-epoch velocity uncertainty.
   182	
   183	## Verification obligations
   184	
   185	Before steering trials, tests shall demonstrate end-to-end execution from real-capture
